    en: "NY Real Property Law section 265-a (the Home Equity Theft Prevention Act, HETPA) protects homeowners in default or facing foreclosure from people who promise to save the home but actually take its equity. Common scams: investor offers to take title and let the homeowner stay as a renter while the investor 'fixes' the loan, then evicts and pockets the equity. HETPA requires every such transaction with a homeowner in default to be in writing with a 5-day right to cancel, prohibits the rescuer from charging upfront fees, requires the homeowner to receive at least 82 percent of the home's fair market value, and gives the homeowner a 2-year right to rescind if anything was not properly disclosed. Violators face civil and criminal penalties. NY Attorney General investigates patterns; private suit available for damages plus return of the property in some cases."
